<script>
function calculateSIP() {
  const m = parseFloat(document.getElementById('monthly_investment').value);
  const r = parseFloat(document.getElementById('ross').value)/100/12;
  const n = parseFloat(document.getElementById('years').value)*12;
  const result = m * ((Math.pow(1+r, n)-1)/r) * (1+r);
  document.getElementById('result').innerText = 'Future Value: ₹' + result.toFixed(0);
}
</script>
<div class="post" id="rbi-policy-update">
  <h2>🏦 RBI Monetary Policy Update – August 6, 2025</h2>
  <p><strong>Repo Rate:</strong> Held steady at <strong>5.50%</strong><br>
     <strong>Policy Stance:</strong> Neutral (unanimous vote by MPC)</p>
  <p><strong>Inflation Outlook:</strong> CPI inflation projected at <strong>3.1%</strong> for FY26, revised from 3.7%. Core inflation steady at ~4.4% (~77-month low headline at 2.1% in June).</p>
  <p><strong>Growth Forecast:</strong> Real GDP growth maintained at <strong>6.5% for FY26</strong>; quarterly growth: Q1–6.5%, Q2–6.7%, Q3–6.6%, Q4–6.3%.</p>
  <p><strong>Liquidity Highlights:</strong> CRR remains at 3%; SDF rate at 5.25%; MSF & Bank rate at 5.75%. Liquidity surplus ~₹3 lakh crore daily; RBI to continue VRRR auctions to manage overnight rates.</p>
  <p><strong>Key Drivers:</strong>  
     – Low inflation allows room for further easing later this year.<br>
     – US tariff developments remain key risk—but impact uncertain.<br>
     – RBI continues to monitor credit transmission and growth-inflation dynamics.</p>
  <p><em>💡 Implication for borrowers: No immediate EMI relief. Sectors like real estate, autos, and consumer durable may remain under pressure as rate-sensitive areas. Markets interpret this as a cautious pause.</em></p>
</div>
<p><small>Source: RBI MPC meeting summary, press reports from Business Standard, Reuters, Hindustan Times, and Economic Times (August 6, 2025).</small></p>
